22 Preamble
23 WHEREAS, The American Psychological Association, the American Psychiatric
24 Association, the American Academy of Pediatrics, the American Medical Association, the
25 American Counseling Association, the American Academy of Child and Adolescent
26 Psychiatry, the American School Counselor Association, the National Association of Social
27 Workers, and every other mainstream mental health and medical organization in the
28 United States have determined that efforts to change an individual’s sexual orientation or
29 gender identity are harmful and ineffective; and
30 WHEREAS, In 2009, the American Psychological Association Task Force on
31 Appropriate Therapeutic Responses to Sexual Orientation conducted a systematic review
32 of peer–reviewed research and concluded that sexual orientation change efforts are unlikely
33 to be successful and involve some risk of harm, including depression, suicidality, and
34 anxiety; and
35 WHEREAS, In 2021, the American Psychological Association adopted a resolution
36 concluding that gender identity change efforts are harmful and ineffective and calling for
37 their elimination; and
38 WHEREAS, The scientific and clinical consensus establishes that conversion
39 therapy poses serious risks of harm to patients, including depression, guilt, helplessness,

HOUSE BILL 1209 3
1 hopelessness, shame, social withdrawal, suicidality, substance abuse, stress, self–blame,
2 decreased self–esteem, feelings of anger and betrayal, loss of religious faith, alienation from
3 family, problems in sexual and emotional intimacy, sexual dysfunction, high–risk sexual
4 behaviors, feelings of being dehumanized, and a sense of having wasted time and resources;
5 and
6 WHEREAS, The psychological harms caused by conversion therapy often do not
7 manifest until years or decades after the conduct occurred and survivors frequently do not
8 recognize their experience as conversion therapy, initially fail to recognize such treatment
9 as harmful, fail to connect their psychological injuries to the treatment until much later in
10 life, or are deterred from coming forward by shame instilled by the treatment itself; and
11 WHEREAS, The dynamics of the therapeutic relationship, including the trust placed
12 in mental health providers, the age and vulnerability of patients, the authority exercised
13 by providers, and the shame and internalized stigma resulting from such treatment, create
14 barriers to timely disclosure and recognition of harm similar to those recognized by this
15 State in the context of childhood sexual abuse; and
16 WHEREAS, The existing statute of limitations for professional negligence does not
17 adequately account for the delayed recognition of psychological injury that is characteristic
18 of harm caused by conversion therapy; and
19 WHEREAS, Psychological harms caused by conversion therapy result from efforts to
20 direct a patient toward a predetermined outcome regarding the patient’s sexual orientation
21 or gender identity, regardless of the nature of that predetermined outcome; and
22 WHEREAS, In cases involving latent injuries where there is scientific consensus
23 regarding harmfulness, courts have recognized that plaintiffs may establish causation by
24 demonstrating that exposure to the harmful conduct was, in reasonable medical
25 probability, a substantial factor contributing to the risk of developing the injury or illness,
26 without requiring proof of the precise mechanism by which the harm occurred; and
27 WHEREAS, This causation framework is appropriate for claims arising from sexual
28 orientation or gender identity change efforts, given the scientific consensus regarding the
29 harmfulness of such efforts and the latent nature of the resulting psychological injuries;
30 and
31 WHEREAS, It is the intent of the General Assembly to provide individuals who have
32 suffered harm as a result of conversion therapy by licensed mental health providers with
33 adequate time to seek civil remedies for harm they have suffered; now, therefore,
34 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
35 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
36 Article – Courts and Judicial Proceedings
